<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<?import javafx.scene.control.*?>
<?import javafx.scene.layout.*?>

<VBox xmlns="http://javafx.com/javafx/17" xmlns:fx="http://javafx.com/fxml/1" fx:controller="" alignment="CENTER" spacing="10">
    <Label text="Manager Login" styleClass="title-label" />

    <HBox alignment="CENTER" spacing="10">
        <Label text="Username:" />
        <TextField fx:id="usernameField" />
    </HBox>

    <HBox alignment="CENTER" spacing="10">
        <Label text="Password:" />
        <PasswordField fx:id="passwordField" />
    </HBox>

    <Button text="Login" onAction="#handleLoginButtonAction" />

    <!-- Add styling for your UI elements in an external CSS file -->
    <!-- For example: <Button text="Login" onAction="#handleLoginButtonAction" styleClass="login-button" /> -->
</VBox>




In these FXML files, placeholders like your.package.ManagerLogin, your.package.CashierView, and your.package.ManagerDashboard should be replaced with the actual package names where your Java controller classes (ManagerLogin, CashierView, and ManagerDashboard) are located.

These FXML files define the basic structure of your UI screens. You can further customize and style them using CSS as needed. Make sure to define the necessary event handlers (e.g., onAction="#handleLoginButtonAction") to link the FXML buttons to the corresponding methods in your Java controller classes.





